The document was too long to read directly, so here is a detailed summary of all sections:

The paper "A Business by Any Other Name: Firm Name Choice as a Signal of Firm Quality" by Ryan C. McDevitt explores how the name of a firm, specifically plumbing firms, can signal information about its quality. McDevitt's study shows that plumbing firms whose names begin with "A" or a number tend to receive significantly more service complaints and charge higher prices compared to others. An analysis of the market reveals that these "A" named firms have five times more complaints to the Better Business Bureau and three times more complaints per employee than other firms. 

Moreover, these firms typically spend more on advertising in the Yellow Pages and on Google, with a positive correlation between advertising spending and the number of complaints received. The market data from Dun & Bradstreet indicate that "A" firms have similar sales-to-employee ratios as other companies, while data from platforms like Angie's List and Yelp demonstrate that these firms receive worse average ratings.

McDevitt reconciles these findings with a model where firms differ in quality and consumers have varying search costs. In larger markets, the prevalence of "A" naming strategies suggests many customers are attracted to early listings in search results, supporting models predicting search cost-related price premiums for firms listed first. Empirically, "A" firms capture an 8.4% price premium.

The paper argues that firms choose their names to attract specific types of customers based on their underlying quality, and those using names starting with “A” or numbers prefer to attract customers with lower search engagement. In smaller markets, the role of reputation and lower search costs means that high-quality firms depend less on name positioning for attracting customers. 

